      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Next Chapter</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Marge Lambert letter on July 16 issue on race in America recalls growing up in small, all-white Catholic community where residents, mostly of Russian, Polish or Slovak descent, feared intermarriage</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>I grew up in a small, lower-middle-class, all-white, Catholic town. Most of the population was of Russian, Polish or Slovak descent. The residents weren't concerned with race issues, but they feared, if Polish, say, that their children would marry a Russian or Slovak or an Italian or Irish kid.</p>
        <p>It would seem that prejudices find a way regardless of the homogeneity of the community.</p>
        <p>Marge Lambert  New York</p>
      </block>
